    ## BRCA1 — Expert Analysis
    **Core function.** BRCA1 is the central scaffold of the homologous recombination (HR) DNA repair pathway. The 1,863-aa nuclear phosphoprotein (P38398) operates as an E3 ubiquitin ligase forming K6-linked polyubiquitin chains, and assembles the BRCA1-associated genome surveillance complex (BASC) with MSH2/6, MLH1, ATM, BLM, and the RAD50-MRE11-NBS1 complex. Its tandem BRCT domains read phospho-SXXF motifs on partners (Abraxas, BACH1/BRIP1, CtIP), routing the cell between HR, single-strand annealing, and end-joining at double-strand breaks. Loss of BRCA1 collapses HR fidelity and forces error-prone NHEJ, producing the chromosomal instability and signature-3 mutational pattern characteristic of BRCA1-deficient tumors.
    **Clinical significance.** Germline loss-of-function variants in BRCA1 (17q21.31) confer ~65–72% lifetime breast cancer risk and ~40–45% ovarian cancer risk, with elevated risk for fallopian tube, peritoneal, and pancreatic cancer. The gene is the prototype tumor suppressor under Knudson two-hit kinetics — heterozygous carriers lose the wild-type allele somatically. BRCA1-mutant tumors are overwhelmingly triple-negative, basal-like, and high-grade, with distinct biology from BRCA2-mutant disease (which skews ER+ and includes male breast and prostate cancer).
    **Therapeutic implication — synthetic lethality.** HR-deficient BRCA1-null cells are exquisitely sensitive to PARP inhibition (olaparib, talazoparib, niraparib, rucaparib) and platinum chemotherapy, because they cannot resolve the replication-fork lesions these agents generate. This is now standard of care: PARPi maintenance in BRCA-mutant ovarian cancer (SOLO-1, PAOLA-1) and adjuvant olaparib in high-risk early breast cancer (OlympiA) both produce durable survival benefit. Acquired resistance routes — secondary reversion mutations restoring the reading frame, 53BP1/RIF1/Shieldin loss restoring end resection, and replication fork stabilization — are now the dominant clinical resistance mechanism and a major research front.
    **Experimental implications.** Any functional study of BRCA1 must distinguish HR scaffold function (BRCT/RING domains) from ubiquitin ligase activity, since separation-of-function alleles (e.g., I26A in the RING) preserve tumor suppression in mouse models despite ablating E3 activity — meaning E3 catalysis is dispensable for the cancer-relevant phenotype. Variants of uncertain significance (VUS) remain a major clinical bottleneck and are best resolved by saturation genome editing (Findlay et al.) or HDR-based functional assays rather than in silico prediction. For models, use isogenic BRCA1-null lines (SUM149PT, HCC1937, MDA-MB-436) with re-expression controls; avoid drawing pathway conclusions from BRCA2-null systems, as the two genes are non-redundant despite overlapping HR phenotypes.

